post_text:
Unfortunately, we've got a bit of bad news to share. Due to a scheduling conflict, our Pixellot system installation is delayed until Sept. 24, which means we're hoping our first live streamed event to be on Sept. 25 through the system. We'll have cameras on Linden Field and in the high school gymnasium.

We are eager to start using this new system and we promise to share it with you as soon as it's ready.

In the mean time, our staff will try to live stream as many events as we can on our YouTube channel to accommodate for parents and fans who cannot attend events. Thank you in advance for your patience and understanding.

The General McLane School Board of Education will meet for its Monthly Agenda Meeting on Wednesday, Sept. 16, 2020, at 6:30 p.m.

The Board will meet in person, but is inviting the public to attend via Zoom. This is due to the publicly advertised space (the Board Room), not having enough space to accommodate visitors and the Board Members and appropriately socially distance from one another.

If you'd like to attend or speak at the meeting, please email Sarah Grabski at sarahgrabski@generalmclane.org. Please keep in mind that if you wish to speak publicly, the Board asks each speaker to identify her/himself by using a first and last name and some sort of geographical location.

post_text: üá∫üá∏ The tragic events of Sept. 11, 2001, changed the U.S. and the world forever. For those who were old enough to watch those events unfold, that day and the aftermath of the attacks has left an indelible mark. For those too young to remember, the legacy of 9/11 shapes your lives as a central event in world history. Please take a moment today to consider all of the lives that were lost and changed on that September morning 19 years ago today.

The General McLane School Board of Education will meet in-person on Wednesday, Sept. 9, 2020 at 6:30 p.m. for its monthly study session meeting.

The public is invited to attend via virtual Zoom Webinar again this month due to the publicly-advertised space being too small to accommodate visitors safely while social distancing.

Please note this is a Study Session Meeting and not a Monthly Agenda Meeting, which means Board members will discuss agenda items and different topics that they will vote on the following week at the Monthly Agenda Meeting.

If you're interested in attending or have any questions, please email Board Secretary Sarah Grabski at sarahgrabski@generalmclane.org. The Zoom link will also be posted publicly shortly before the meeting begins.

September 3 at 2:52 PM ¬∑

From the ECED:

Hello Edinboro Community!

The Edinboro Community and Economic Development Board has engaged a community planning organization to help us reimagine and plan for a bright and vibrant Edinboro Community. We invite all interested Edinboro and surrounding area residents, business, and friends to participate by 1) completing a survey which is available until September 25th, and 2) participate in a webinar on Thursday, September 10th from 6 to 7 PM.

‚Ä¢ The survey and registration information for the webinar are both found here: http://edinboroplacemaking.com/

‚Ä¢ Or you can go directly to the survey: www.surveymonkey.com/r/EdinboroPA

‚Ä¢ If you are interested in learning about the consultant group that is guiding us, here is their website: www.alchemycommunities.com

Q: When will we know when the school bus will pick up our student(s)?

A: We realize we're less than a week away from school starting. Our transportation department has worked tirelessly to make the half-day plan happen and to honor as many requests as possible and we know you're waiting patiently to hear those details.

You'll receive a USPS mailed post card with those details soon. They were mailed out Monday-Tuesday. If for some reason you do not receive the post card by Monday when your mail comes, please contact the bus garage (814)273-1033 ext. 6900.

Thank you for your patience with this.

post_text:
We are getting SO many great and thoughtful questions for our Q&A tomorrow. Thanks for sending them in before we go live - that will make our job in addressing all of your concerns and issues easier.

If you're wanting to submit your question ahead of the chat, please email sarahgrabski@generalmclane.org.

We want to emphasize that there will be a transcript of our Q&A that will be on the GM website available within 24 hours of our event, so if we don't get to your question during the live event, it will be answered there.

We also want to thank everyone for their patience and understanding in approaching this 20-21 school year. There are so many uncertainties, but please know that our district and our administration only wants to work with families and parents to keep our kids safe while providing the best education possible.

We are asking every family between now and next Wednesday, June 24, to complete two documents to further assist in our planning for the 2020-2021 school year.

The first is called Parent Survey Form and is a simple 5 question survey about next year. It provides background information to help you answer the questions: https://www.generalmclane.net/parent-survey-form/

The other is called the Parent Commitment Form which we ask you to fill out for each of your children, telling us your intent for education plans for next year: https://www.generalmclane.net/parent-commitment-form/

Both can also be found by accessing our home page, generalmclane.org.

Thank you, GM families, for helping us plan for what we're sure will be an amazing 2020-2021 school year!

McKean Elementary PTA and James W. Parker Middle School PTSA, part of the Erie County Council of PTAs, will host a drive-thru plant event called ‚ÄúPTA is Rooting for You‚Äù on Saturday, June 6.

The event will be from 9 to 11 a.m., at St. Francis Xavier Church, 8880 Main St., McKean.

Each family will receive four plants to plant at home to get fresh produce of their own later this summer.

Families do not need to be part of a PTA or even attend a school with a PTA. They just need to live in Erie County. post_text:
PUBLIC NOTICE: The General McLane Board of Education is hosting its monthly Study Session on Wednesday, May 13, 2020, on Zoom at the recommendation of the Pennsylvania Office of Open Records in response to COVID-19.

The public is invited to attend. If you wish to make a comment for the Board or attend via Zoom, please send an email to Sarah Grabski, sarahgrabski@generalmclane.org. Note: Board members cannot discuss any comments received by email before the meeting. Please also note that you will only be allowed to participate during the public comment sections. We will also share the link publicly before the meeting on Wednesday.

The agenda for Wednesday can be found on our website, generalmclane.net, under Departments > School Board > Agendas/Minutes.

post_text:
The Community Blood Bank will host a blood drive in its Bloodmobile stationed in the General McLane High School parking lot on May 13 from 10 a.m. to 2 p.m.

For social distancing purposes, the blood bank will only allow 2-3 donors on the mobile in addition to staff. Additional donors are asked to wait in their vehicles until they are called to the mobile for prescreening.

Donors must be at least 17 years or older or 16 with parental consent, weigh at least 110 pounds, have no tattoos or body piercings within the last 12 months, be in general good health and eat before donating.

Please help our GM photography students and vote for this week's Photo of the Week!

GMHS photo students have been learning photography ONLINE. They are focused on learning their devices (mostly phones) to create great photo compositions. This week they were introduced to 5 BIG RULES in composition and were asked to ELIMINATE all distractions and surroundings to make an almost "abstract" composition. They eliminated distractions so that they could focus on a focal point, its placement, and creation eye direction.

Please help us decide who will win PHOTO OF THE WEEK!

post_text:
Even apart...we are better together. GM Class of 2020, we understand the next few months will not be easy for you.

"Until we can be together again, I want you to reinvent the end of your senior year by participating in something I‚Äôm calling, 'Even apart . . .we are better together.' I encourage you to find a way to share the memories and experiences of your GM years with each other: make a short video talking about your experiences and friendships; put together a slide show of your years in school; create a drawing, painting or photograph representing who you are; record yourself singing or playing a song; if you‚Äôre into writing, write about your experiences or how you feel about this pandemic; Find a way to express yourself and share it with us; we will have a 'Better Together' webpage on our school district website and share on our social media outlets."

Every 10 years, the U.S. Census Bureau undertakes a mammoth task: counting all the people residing in the United States.

This count affects the allocation of funding for our community‚Äôs public resources (e.g., roads, hospitals, schools), how we plan for the future and our voice in government.

Edinboro, we need your help. Only 41 percent of our residents have filled out the 2020 Census and we are lagging behind the rest of Erie County. Please take a few minutes to help General McLane SD and fill out yours today!

Superintendent Rick Scaletta addresses this topic in his Lancer Letter here: https://www.generalmclane.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Lancer-Letter-475-2020-Census.pdf

post_text:
PUBLIC NOTICE: The General McLane Board of Education is hosting its monthly Study Session and Limited Agenda Meeting on Wednesday, April 15, 2020, on Zoom at the recommendation of the Pennsylvania Office of Open Records in response to COVID-19.

The public is invited to attend. If you wish to make a comment for the Board or attend via Zoom, please send an email to Sarah Grabski, sarahgrabski@generalmclane.org. Note: Board members cannot discuss any comments received by email before the meeting. Please also note that you will only be allowed to participate during the public comment sections. We will also share the link publicly before the meeting on Wednesday.

The agenda for Wednesday can be found on our website, generalmclane.net, under Departments > School Board > Agendas/Minutes.

post_text:
At this time, no decisions have been made regarding the cancellation or rescheduling of end of year events. We feel that, at this time, enough is not known to make an informed decision. The earliest a decision would be made is April 30, unless unforeseen or unknown circumstances present themselves.

Our top priority is graduation. Our strong preference is for a live event, even if that means scheduling it in the summer. If the situation with the pandemic prevents that, we will find someway to note the end of the time that the class of 2020 has spent at General McLane.

post_text: Our superintendent Richard Scaletta recorded this week's Lancer Letter in a video message. He's talking about the COVID-19 pandemic and offering some positivity to students, parents and community members. Hear what he has to say:
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM

We're beginning planned online instruction on Monday, March 30. For families or students who do not have Wi-Fi access, we've created "hot spots" around our schools that will allow students or families to drive up, download their assignments, complete them, drive back up and upload them.

These maps show where those "hot spots" are surrounding our schools. To connect, students/families will need their school passwords. Parents: no worries, the connection isn't fast enough (and has filters) so kids won't be playing Angry Birds or Candy Crush :)

These will be active starting Monday. If you have further questions, don't hesitate to contact us.

post_text:
The Department of Education (PDE) announced today all schools in the commonwealth will remain closed through at least April 6 as a result of the COVID-19 response efforts. The closure order could be extended beyond April 6 if necessary to save lives and stop the spread of COVID-19.

Under the new timeline, school buildings would reopen on April 7 for two days to allow school administrators, teachers and other staff time to prepare classrooms, set up cafeterias, schedule transportation and arrange other business operations. Students would return to school on April 9, unless extending the closure is needed in response to the situation with the virus at that time.

More instructions and planning specific to the GM community will follow in the next few days. As Mr. Scaletta says: stay tuned, stay healthy and eat those fruits and vegetables.

Wolf‚Äôs statement came hours after his secretary of education, Pedro Rivera, told superintendents statewide that the decision to close schools would be up to local school districts.

General McLane to use flexible day to prepare for virus
text:
Thank you GoErie.com | Erie Times-News for sharing this with community members. We are going to be practicing a "Flexible Instructional Day" on Friday, March 13, 2020.

GOERIE.COM
General McLane to use flexible day to prepare for virus

post_text:
Attention GM Parents: Friday, March 13, 2020, will be used as a Flexible Instructional Day. Students will not report to school but will be learning from home that day.

Given that the Center for Disease Control has asked that schools prepare, plan and practice contingency plans in the event that the Coronavirus pandemic shuts down schools, we have decided to conduct our snow make-up day as a FID on March 13, giving teachers and students the opportunity to ‚Äúpractice‚Äù for unforeseen circumstances.

This will count as the make-up day for the February 27, 2020 snow day that closed all GM schools.

PLEASE see the FAQ on our home page right now for answers to questions you may have. Thank you, in advance, for your cooperation.

Our website: https://www.generalmclane.net/

post_text: Tom & Tom were in the house today for another stellar presentation!
shared_text:
JET/FOX/YourErie
October 29, 2019 at 6:57 PM ¬∑

One more big shout out to Science Teacher Laurie Santos (pictured in the first shot here-upper left) and her crew and James W. Parker Middle School for a great school visit this afternoon. It's rare that Tom D. and I get to go to a weather talk together, but this place was rocking! There were 6 videos made by the students to welcome us. There were 166 science students of Mrs. Santos jammed into one room and the students had prepared questions for Tom & me from the get go. The visit was recorded live on this Facebook page and is in the video section. Thanks to a great student body, teachers and administration for making us feel so welcome.

post_text:
The transformation of James W. Parker Middle School to Trail of Treats-ready is currently underway! Be sure to see what the school looks like tomorrow at the sixth annual Trail of Treats Fundraiser!

Children are invited to gather candy and treats at various stations set up throughout the Middle School between 1 p.m. and 3 p.m. This event is for children 12 and under and the cost is $3 per child. An adult must accompany any child throughout this event. Costumes are encouraged, but not required.

This year, all proceeds will benefit James W. Parker Middle School‚Äôs PBIS program.

post_text: Did you know that General McLane High School has a new ‚Äúprotein to go‚Äù cart stationed in the gym lobby every morning? As students come in from the bus, they can use their 4-digit code to get hard boiled eggs, yogurt and fruit parfaits, meat and cheese breakfast sandwiches or quality protein bars, as well as fruit. This was funded through a grant that was part of Pennsylvania Governor Tom Wolf's school breakfast initiative and is meant to provide students with alternative breakfast methods to fuel better academic performance.

post_text: Did you know JWPMS has a YouTube superstar? Sixth grader Lilly has over 17,000 subscribers to her YouTube channel, CheezitVlogz! Lilly recently met with McKean Elementary 4th graders as an extension to their career exploration standards. She gave a nice overview of her journey in this field and answered a ton of prepared questions from students including topics about getting permission to post about friends, code-names to protect identity, how she gains so many subscribers, who inspired her, etc. The kids were amazed by her and were soaking in every bit of information.
